{"Body": "<p>The numbers of students in Trinity College Dublin seeking help for mental health difficulties has doubled to 107 in the past year, according to a five year report on the Unilink service released last week.</p>\n<p>Established in 2004, Unilink offers one-on-one sessions with qualified occupational therapists to students referred with mental health issues including Asperger&rsquo;s Syndrome, Attention Deficit Disorder, Depression and Eating Disorders.&nbsp; These various difficulties can often impede the student&rsquo;s ability to participate both academically and socially in college life.</p>\n<p>The transition into an unknown environment directly after completing stressful end of school exams can be an overwhelming experience for any Freshman. <br />Final year students are subjected to intense academic pressure as they, too, enter a life altering period. These already hectic times can be exacerbated in some cases by pre-existing mental difficulties.</p>\n<p>It is therefore unsurprising that the main disorder students come to UniLink with is depression, often brought on by excessive stress. Predictably, large peaks in those availing of the services are observable in the first and final year student population.</p>\n<p>According to Clodagh Nolan, Head of Occupational Therapy at TCD,&nbsp; &ldquo;The focus of this occupational therapy programme is on the &lsquo;here and now&rsquo; and on the &lsquo;doing&rsquo; to enable students to manage their mental health difficulties and achieve their degree.&nbsp; Often individuals with mental health problems have capacity for intellectual engagement and achievement but lack the practical know how to put their capacity into practice&rdquo;</p>\n<p>UniLink help develop self management, organisational and study skills through goal setting, timetabling and other exercises whilst also teaching the basics of social interaction and non-verbal communication with interactive role plays.<br />Trinity College Dublin is the first university in Ireland to provide such a practical occupational programme to its students. These services could not have come at a more appropriate time. A survey from the Association for Higher Education Access and Disability (AHEAD) states that in the past 10 years the numbers of students in third level education with disabilities has risen by almost 250%, with nearly 380 suffering from mental health issues.</p>\n<p>Stiof&aacute;n &Oacute; Broin, Trinity Students&rsquo; Union&rsquo;s Officer for Students with Disabilities, said &ldquo;UniLink has been successful. There&rsquo;s always been a great demand for help in Trinity. A lot of services are there for the students, they&rsquo;re just not being used. Some of the main problems are that students don&rsquo;t know they exist or they&rsquo;re worried there might be a stigma attached to registering with the services&hellip; It can be a bit daunting sometimes to make appointments with people you don&rsquo;t know but you can talk to me,&nbsp; the Welfare Officer, your tutor, or the disability services.&rdquo;<br />&Oacute; Broin went on to say that anyone who wishs to avail of any of the services available to those with mental health issues should contact the Mental Health Service about UniLink.</p>", "Imageurl": "<p>The numbers of students in Trinity College Dublin seeking help for mental health difficulties has doubled to 107 in the past year, according to a five year report on the Unilink service released last week.</p>\n<p>Established in 2004, Unilink offers one-on-one sessions with qualified occupational therapists to students referred with mental health issues including Asperger&rsquo;s Syndrome, Attention Deficit Disorder, Depression and Eating Disorders.&nbsp; These various difficulties can often impede the student&rsquo;s ability to participate both academically and socially in college life.</p>\n<p>The transition into an unknown environment directly after completing stressful end of school exams can be an overwhelming experience for any Freshman. <br />Final year students are subjected to intense academic pressure as they, too, enter a life altering period. These already hectic times can be exacerbated in some cases by pre-existing mental difficulties.</p>\n<p>It is therefore unsurprising that the main disorder students come to UniLink with is depression, often brought on by excessive stress. Predictably, large peaks in those availing of the services are observable in the first and final year student population.</p>\n<p>According to Clodagh Nolan, Head of Occupational Therapy at TCD,&nbsp; &ldquo;The focus of this occupational therapy programme is on the &lsquo;here and now&rsquo; and on the &lsquo;doing&rsquo; to enable students to manage their mental health difficulties and achieve their degree.&nbsp; Often individuals with mental health problems have capacity for intellectual engagement and achievement but lack the practical know how to put their capacity into practice&rdquo;</p>\n<p>UniLink help develop self management, organisational and study skills through goal setting, timetabling and other exercises whilst also teaching the basics of social interaction and non-verbal communication with interactive role plays.<br />Trinity College Dublin is the first university in Ireland to provide such a practical occupational programme to its students. These services could not have come at a more appropriate time. A survey from the Association for Higher Education Access and Disability (AHEAD) states that in the past 10 years the numbers of students in third level education with disabilities has risen by almost 250%, with nearly 380 suffering from mental health issues.</p>\n<p>Stiof&aacute;n &Oacute; Broin, Trinity Students&rsquo; Union&rsquo;s Officer for Students with Disabilities, said &ldquo;UniLink has been successful. There&rsquo;s always been a great demand for help in Trinity. A lot of services are there for the students, they&rsquo;re just not being used. Some of the main problems are that students don&rsquo;t know they exist or they&rsquo;re worried there might be a stigma attached to registering with the services&hellip; It can be a bit daunting sometimes to make appointments with people you don&rsquo;t know but you can talk to me,&nbsp; the Welfare Officer, your tutor, or the disability services.&rdquo;<br />&Oacute; Broin went on to say that anyone who wishs to avail of any of the services available to those with mental health issues should contact the Mental Health Service about UniLink.</p>", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "390", "Heading": "Number of Trinity students using mental health services doubles"}